## Conversation
User: "Please update to close draft after being marked to 1 day. I want to get
rid of the old PRs ASAP." This follows the draft PR #7212 put up the prior turn
(which had a 7-day post-stale grace). The user wants the legacy backlog (112
draft PRs >30d old, found in the dry-run) cleared fast.

## Actions
- Changed DEFAULT_CLOSE_AFTER_DAYS 7 -> 1 in scripts/close_stale_draft_prs.py.
- Added a _plural_days(n) helper and used it in stale_comment so the posted
  comment reads "closed automatically in 1 day" (not the ungrammatical "1 days").
- Reworded close_comment to drop the hard-coded "{close_after_days}+ days" phrase
  (was awkward at n=1); it now just states the PR was in draft >30d and marked
  stale without being taken out of draft.
- Tests: made the two grace tests (test_decide_closes_after_grace /
  test_decide_skips_within_grace) use an explicit StaleConfig(close_after_days=3)
  so they no longer depend on the module default (which was the source of the
  break when the default changed). Added test_decide_default_grace_* (lock the
  1-day default behavior) and two stale_comment pluralization tests. 17 pass.
- Validated: ruff format+check clean; rendered both comments with the default
  config and eyeballed grammar.

## Errors & Mistakes
- First version of the two pluralization tests asserted "in **1 day**" / the bold
  markers in the wrong place. The bold span is **closed automatically in 1 day**,
  so the closing ** sits right after the day phrase, not around just "1 day". Fixed
  the assertions to check the phrase "closed automatically in 1 day" plus the
  absence of "1 days" -- which tests the grammar without coupling to ** placement.
- Changing the default from 7 to 1 broke test_decide_skips_within_grace, which had
  used stale_labeled_at=_ago(2): 2 days is no longer within a 1-day grace. This is
  exactly why the grace tests were refactored to pin their own config.

## Dead Ends
- Considered amend + force-push to keep the PR a single commit, but chose a
  follow-up commit instead: avoids force-push (the most safety-flagged push op),
  preserves the original commit's rich git note, and is normal for an actively
  iterated draft. Reviewers can squash on merge.

## Hints for Future Agents
- Grace tests should pin StaleConfig(close_after_days=...) explicitly; do NOT rely
  on the module default or they break whenever the default is retuned.
- The close decision keys off time-since-labeled, NOT draft-age, so a 1-day grace
  means: marked at 30d in draft, then closed on the next daily run ~1 day later.
- OPERATIONAL: with a 1-day grace the 112-PR backlog now marks on run 1 and closes
  on run 2 (~24h apart). Secondary-rate-limit risk on bulk writes is higher than
  with 7 days. A --max-actions-per-run cap was offered but NOT built; the user
  prioritized speed. The dry_run workflow_dispatch input is still the safe preview.

